<subSubSection pageId="71" pageNumber="72" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="71.[151,1437,479,974]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,623,649]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Remarks</emphasis>
. This species is widely spread in Eurasia but very rare in the Far East, known only from small series of specimens from 
<collectingCountry box="[367,435,660,686]" name="South Korea" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Korea</collectingCountry>
(Shinohara 1995) and 
<collectingRegion box="[692,805,659,685]" country="Japan" name="Hokkaido" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Hokkaido</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[817,881,660,686]" name="Japan" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Japan</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Shinohara, A. &amp; Hara, H." box="[895,1179,659,686]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" pagination="193 - 194" refId="ref77591" refString="Shinohara, A. &amp; Hara, H. (1997 a) Pamphilius histrio (Hymenoptera, Pamphiliidae) found in Hokkaido, the first record from Japan. Japanese Journal of Entomology, Tokyo, 65, 193 - 194." type="journal article" year="1997">Shinohara &amp; Hara 1997a</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Shinohara, A. &amp; Hara, H." box="[1191,1250,659,685]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" pagination="123 - 128" refId="ref77685" refString="Shinohara, A. &amp; Hara, H. (1999) Host-plant records for six pamphiliine sawflies (Hymenoptera: Pamphiliidae) in Hokkaido, Japan. Bulletin of the National Science Museum, Tokyo, Series A, 25, 123 - 128." type="journal article" year="1999">1999</bibRefCitation>
, 2005). We have seen no specimens from the Russian Far East. This species is the sole representative of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1812" box="[1159,1261,695,721]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Pamphilius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="histrio">
<emphasis box="[1159,1261,695,721]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">P. histrio</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
subgroup of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1812" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Pamphilius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="histrio">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">P. histrio</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="71.[151,1437,479,974]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">
In our molecular analysis using COI (
<figureCitation box="[618,715,767,793]" captionStart="FIGURES 142–143" captionStartId="230.[151,264,1911,1935]" captionTargetBox="[157,1426,182,1875]" captionTargetId="figure-26@230.[151,1436,181,1887]" captionTargetPageId="230" captionText="FIGURES 142–143. Condensed ML tree based on CO1 gene sequences, with details of Pamphilius 142. histrio group. 143. inanitus group." pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Fig. 142</figureCitation>
), the specimens of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1812" box="[929,1029,767,793]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Pamphilius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="histrio">
<emphasis box="[929,1029,767,793]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">P. histrio</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
formed a clade but it was rather distantly located from the clades represented by five other species of the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1812" box="[933,1034,803,829]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Pamphilius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="histrio">
<emphasis box="[933,1034,803,829]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">P. histrio</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group (
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Kontuniemi" authorityYear="1958" box="[1122,1276,803,829]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Pamphilius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevicornis">
<emphasis box="[1122,1276,803,829]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">P. brevicornis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[1290,1429,803,829]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Pamphilius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gyllenhali">
<emphasis box="[1290,1429,803,829]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">P. gyllenhali</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<emphasis box="[151,382,839,865]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">
<taxonomicName box="[151,263,839,865]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Pamphilius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tricolor">P. tricolor</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[274,382,839,865]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Pamphilius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="betulae">P. betulae</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[436,546,839,865]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Pamphilius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="festivus">
<emphasis box="[436,546,839,865]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">P. festivus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). In the NaK analysis, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1812" box="[801,901,839,865]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Pamphilius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="histrio">
<emphasis box="[801,901,839,865]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">P. histrio</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was not treated. The COI result was in line with the cladistic analysis based on morphology (Shinohara 1995), where 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1812" box="[919,1019,875,901]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Pamphilius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="histrio">
<emphasis box="[919,1019,875,901]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">P. histrio</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was situated remotely from the clade including the three species given above. The monophyly of the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1812" box="[855,955,911,937]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Pamphilius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="histrio">
<emphasis box="[855,955,911,937]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">P. histrio</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group as a whole was not supported by our molecular study as noted in the remarks for the species group.
</paragraph>
